  "prompt": "Who invented immunofluorescence? What purpose does it serve?",
  "response": "**Immunofluorescence** was invented by **Albert Coons**, **Hugh J. Creech**, and **R. Norman Jones** in the early 1940s. Albert Coons is often credited as the principal inventor of this technique. They developed it to detect specific antigens in tissues using antibodies labeled with fluorescent dyes.\n\n### Purpose of Immunofluorescence:\nImmunofluorescence serves as a powerful technique in biological and medical research for **visualizing and localizing specific proteins, antigens, or other biomolecules** within cells, tissues, or microorganisms. It combines the specificity of antibodies with the sensitivity of fluorescence microscopy, enabling researchers to:\n\n1. **Identify and Localize Antigens:** Detect the presence and distribution of specific proteins or other molecules in tissues or cells.\n2. **Study Cellular Structures:** Visualize organelles, cytoskeletal components, and other cellular structures.\n3. **Diagnose Diseases:** Identify pathogens (e.g., viruses, bacteria) or abnormal proteins in clinical samples.\n4. **Understand Disease Mechanisms:** Investigate protein interactions, signaling pathways, and cellular processes in health and disease.\n5. **Track Molecules Over Time:** Observe the dynamics of molecules in live or fixed cells.\n\n### How It Works:\n1. **Primary Antibodies:** Bind specifically to the target antigen.\n2. **Fluorescently Labeled Secondary Antibodies:** Bind to the primary antibodies and emit light when excited by specific wavelengths of light.\n3. **Fluorescence Microscopy:** Used to visualize the fluorescence, revealing the location and abundance of the target molecule.\n\nImmunofluorescence has become a cornerstone technique in immunology, cell biology, pathology, and many other fields.",
